04208nam a22005175i 9780804797924DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20201998cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047979247 a10.1515/97808047979242doi  a(DE-B1597)564928  a(OCoLC)1178768924  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aDS793.S62bM535 1998eb 7aHIS0080002bisacsh04a951/.6222  aPW 94602rvk0(DE-625)rvk/141005:1 aMillward, James A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeyond the Pass :bEconomy, Ethnicity, and Empire in Qing Central Asia, 1759-1864 /cJames A. Millward. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©1998  a1 online resource (380 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tCONTENTS -- tMAPS, FIGURES, AND TABLES -- tPREFACE -- tNOTE ON TRANSLITERATION -- tABBREVIATIONS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. LANDMARKS -- t2. FINANCING NEW DOMINION -- t3. OFFICIAL COMMERCE AND COMMERCIAL TAXATION IN THE FAR WEST -- t4. "GATHERING LIKE CLOUDS": CHINESE MERCANTILE PENETRATION OF XINJIANG -- t5. THE MERCHANTS AND ARTICLES OF TRADE -- t6. QING ETHNIC POLICY AND CHINESE MERCHANTS -- tCONCLUSION: TOWARD THE DOMESTICATION OF EMPIRE -- tCHARACTER LIST -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs analysis of the revenue available to Qing garrisons in Xinjiang reveals, imperial control over the region in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries depended upon sizeable yearly subsidies from China. In an effort to satisfy criticism of their expansion into Xinjiang and make the territory pay for itself, the Qing court permitted local authorities great latitude in fiscal matters and encouraged the presence of Han and Chinese Muslim merchants. At the same time, the court recognized the potential for unrest posed by Chinese mercantile penetration of this Muslim, Turkic-speaking area. They consequently attempted, through administrative and legal means, to defend the native Uyghur population against economic depredation. This ethnic policy reflected a conception of the realm that was not Sinocentric, but rather placed the Uyghur on a par with Han Chinese. Both this ethnic policy and Xinjiang's place in the realm shifted following a series of invasions from western Turkestan starting in the 1820's. Because of the economic importance of Chinese merchants and the efficacy of merchant militia in Xinjiang, the Qing court revised its policies in their favor, for the first time allowing permanent Han settlement in the area. At the same time, the court began to advocate provincehood and the Sinicization of Xinjiang as a resolution to the perennial security problem. These shifts, the author argues, marked the beginning of a reconception of China to include Inner Asian lands and peoples-a notion that would, by the twentieth century, become a deeply held tenet of Chinese nationalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aEthnicityxChinaxSinkiang Uighur Autonomous Region. 0aEthnicityzChinazXinjiang Uygur Zizhiqu. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z978311070421140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479792440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804797924423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804797924.jpg  a978-3-11-070421-1  SUP eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles